article.description: New Jersey Nets didn't quit on their lame duck coach. Instead, they gave Byron Scott one of their best defensive efforts of the season.
article.headline: Kidd, Martin take over vs. Jazz
article.linkText: Nets return from rout for win
article.story: EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- The New Jersey Nets had no problems shaking off a 47-point loss or hushing to rest the latest round of speculation about coach Byron Scott's job status. Jason Kidd had 19 points, eight rebounds and eight assists and the Nets played one of their better defensive games in an 87-74 victory over the Utah Jazz Wednesday night. The easy win came just days after the two-time defending Eastern Conference champions suffered their second worst loss in franchise history, a 110-63 setback in Memphis on Saturday. "I knew we would bounce back and play the way we are capable of playing," Scott said after the Nets got back to the .500 level. "We've done pretty good the last six games, we had one bad game. I am looking forward to this next one this week." What made the loss in Memphis equally notable was that Kidd took everyone to task in a loud closed-door team meeting after the game. He reportedly screamed at Scott during the stormy postgame meeting, adding to the tension between the two. Kidd and Scott barely said a word to each other during Wednesday's game but they shared a laugh in the final moments as the Nets won for the fifth time in six games. Kidd refused to speak after the game. He has not spoken for the past two days because he is miffed reporters wrote that he yelled after the Memphis game. "Whatever happened Saturday is over," said Kenyon Martin, who had 22 points and 11 rebounds. "You guys keep bringing it up to try to sell some newspapers. We came out tonight and took care of business, so maybe now you can write something positive." For one of the rare times this season, the Nets looked like the team that dominated the Eastern Conference the past two seasons. They shot 48 percent from the floor, had a 20-0 advantage on the break and outscored Utah 42-18 in the paint. The Jazz scored nine first-quarter points and were held to 38 percent shooting from the field. "I thought they came out and executed their offense well, they stroked us defensively," Utah coach Jerry Sloan said. "It was hard to see anything (negative) from what I saw. I thought they came at us real hard." Kerry Kittles added 12 points and Jason Collins had 10 while facing his twin brother Jarron. The Nets scored the final seven points in the first half to take a 38-30 lead, and they used a 15-4 spurt early in the second half to take a 53-34 lead on a dunk by Richard Jefferson. Utah pulled to 78-67 with 4:06 remaining, but Kidd hit two from the line and made a 3-pointer to keep the Nets comfortably ahead. Raul Lopez had a team-high 15 points for the Jazz, who missed 12 of 31 free-throw attempts. Game Notes: The teams' 22 combined points was the second-lowest point total in NBA history for an opening period. The record low first quarter is 18 by Fort Wayne and Syracuse on Nov. 29, 1956. ... There were 35 fouls called in the first three quarters, 25 in the fourth. ... Nets center Aaron Williams is expected to be sidelined a couple of games with a pulled a groin muscle... Jazz forward Ben Handlogten left the team to be with his wife for the birth of their son, Michael. Utah had only 10 players in uniform.
